comments:
Reddit is an inherently flawed website based around bullying people with unpopular opinions

Unlike most internet forums, where discussion is democratically arranged in a chronological way, so that everyone's opinion is given equal weight, Reddit's whole system is based around a hierarchy where a majority of users bully a minority of users until their posts are obscured or hidden from everyone else. 

More popular opinions are given more value and receive more visibility than others. By default, everything on this site is ordered by how many people agree with it. Your opinion is more visible if it conforms to mob sentiment, and less visible (or invisible) if it doesn't. What kind of platform for discussion is that? How can anyone hope to engage with conflicting viewpoints or ideas when the very fabric of this website is designed to disallow that very thing? Why write out a repy to someone you disagree with when you can just click the little down arrow and get the dopamine rush anyway? Why bother earnestly trying to change someone's mind when you can just insult them and get two hundred people who share your opinion to jump in, dogpile on the other guy, and drive him out of the discussion?

Not to mention the subconscious, psychological effect that assigning numbers to opinions has on people, training them to perceive unpopular views as being inferior or wrong, or the way this system is manipulated to artificially push certain opinions or advertising.

This site was intentionally designed to be a massive echochamber with no divergence or free thought. The crooked moderation, censorship, etc. is all just icing on the cake.
